Hotel Revenue Analysis and Visualization Project
ğŸ“Š Project Overview
This project demonstrates an end-to-end data analysis and visualization workflow. It focuses on analyzing revenue and operational metrics for a hotel business. The dataset was processed and queried using Microsoft SQL Server and visualized in Power BI to provide actionable insights.

ğŸ” Objectives
The project addresses the following key business questions:

Is hotel revenue growing by year?
Should the parking lot sizes be increased?
What trends can we see in the data?

ğŸš€ Tools and Technologies
SQL: Used for data querying and preprocessing in Microsoft SQL Server.
Power BI: Used to create the interactive dashboard for visualization.
ğŸ“ˆ Dashboard Features
The Power BI dashboard provides insights into:

Total Revenue: $10.23M total revenue across all years.
Key Metrics:
Average ADR: $104.47
Total Nights Booked: 367.78K
Average Discount: 25.81%
Car Parking Requirements: 8.69K spaces
Trends Over Time: A time-series analysis of revenue by reservation date and hotel type (City vs. Resort).
Revenue Distribution: Comparison of revenue between City Hotel and Resort Hotel (53.62% vs. 46.38%).
Parking Utilization: Annual trends in parking space requirements.

ğŸ’¡ Key Insights
1. Is hotel revenue growing by year?
Yes. Revenue grew significantly from $1.2M in 2018 to $5.5M in 2019 and $3.5M in 2020 (partial data).
2. Should we increase parking lot size?
No. Parking requirements remained stable, with an average utilization of 2.36%. Expanding the parking lot is unnecessary based on the current data.
3. What trends can we see in the data?
Revenue Trends: Strong growth in 2019, followed by stabilization in 2020.
Hotel Comparison: Resort Hotels contribute slightly more revenue (53.62%) than City Hotels (46.38%).
Operational Metrics: Discounts and ADR remained consistent, with slight fluctuations over time.

